# Summary of Attention is all you need
1)The article or blog introduces a new model architecture called the Transformer, which is based entirely on attention mechanisms and doesn't use recurrence or convolutions.
2)The Transformer model achieves state-of-the-art performance on machine translation tasks, outperforming previous models while being faster to train.
3)The key innovation is the use of "self-attention" allowing the model to attend to different parts of the input sequence when producing each part of the output.
4)The model uses "multi-head attention", which lets it attend to information from different representation subspaces at different positions.
5)Positional encodings are added to the input embeddings to make use of the order of the sequence, since the model contains no recurrence or convolution.
6)The Transformer can be trained significantly faster than architectures based on recurrent or convolutional layers, due to increased parallelization.
7)The model generalizes well to other tasks like English constituency parsing, even with limited task-specific tuning.
8)The authors suggest the Transformer may be useful for other sequence transduction tasks beyond just text, like for images, audio or video.
9)The article provides visualizations showing how different attention heads in the model learn to perform different tasks, like focusing on relevant words or handling long-distance dependencies.
10)The authors are excited about the future potential of attention-based models and plan to extend this approach to other tasks and modalities.
